---
import DocLayout from "../../layouts/DocLayout.astro";
import ApiEntry from "../../components/docs/ApiEntry.astro";
import Example from "../../components/docs/Example.astro";
---

<DocLayout
  title="Skills"
  eyebrow="AI agent integration"
  description="OpenPress ships agent skills that wire Claude / Cursor / Codex / Copilot / Gemini directly into the workspace. Skills are split into active workflows (slash commands) and a knowledge layer (handbook chapters)."
>
  <p>
    The OpenPress framework installs agent-readable skills into every workspace
    (<code>.agents/skills/</code> for universal tools, plus per-platform mirrors under
    <code>.claude/skills/</code>, <code>.cursor/skills/</code>, etc.). Skills are how agents stay
    aware of the framework's conventions without re-reading the entire codebase.
  </p>

  <h2>Two kinds of skill content</h2>

  <p>
    The skills repo is moving toward a clean split:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Active skills</strong> — discrete <em>workflows</em> an agent invokes. They take an
      intake, decide a plan, run commands, and report. In modern AI tools these surface as
      <em>slash commands</em>: <code>/create-document</code>, <code>/create-theme</code>,
      <code>/apply-comments</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Handbook content</strong> — the reference an agent reads while doing work (style
      rules, design system, deploy flow). This is the same material as <code>/docs/*</code> on
      this site; the long-term plan is for the dogfood document to be the single source.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Active skills</h2>

  <p>
    Type these triggers in any AI tool that has read the OpenPress skill bundle (Claude Code,
    Cursor, Codex CLI, Copilot, Gemini CLI, …). The trigger phrase appears in each skill's
    description, so agents recognise the slash form even though they're not formal slash-command
    files.
  </p>

  <ApiEntry
    name="/create-document"
    kind="command"
    importFrom="/create-document"
    summary="Scaffold a new OpenPress workspace from intake. Gathers document type / audience / language / metadata, picks a style pack, runs the init CLI, and reports first-build status."
  >
    <p>
      Routes to the same <code>@open-press/cli init</code> command an author calls manually
      (<a href="/docs/cli/lifecycle">CLI · Lifecycle</a>). The skill exists to make agent intake
      explicit — what title, what audience, what pack — instead of agents guessing. Lives in
      <code>skills/openpress-init/</code>.
    </p>
  </ApiEntry>

  <ApiEntry
    name="/create-theme"
    kind="command"
    importFrom="/create-theme"
    summary="Build or refine document/theme/. Intakes brand identity and content type, picks a base preset, writes tokens.css + page-surfaces/, hands back a workbench session for visual verification."
  >
    <p>
      Follows the <a href="/docs/themes">theme directory contract</a>. Output is a fully populated
      <code>document/theme/</code> that the user can edit further; the skill never hand-codes
      one-off visuals. Lives in <code>skills/openpress-create-theme/</code>.
    </p>
  </ApiEntry>

  <ApiEntry
    name="/apply-comments"
    kind="command"
    importFrom="/apply-comments"
    summary="Resolve pending @openpress-comment markers. For each marker: read the surrounding prose, decide on an edit, apply it, delete the marker. Reports which were handled vs left for human judgement."
  >
    <p>
      The contract is documented at <a href="/docs/comments">Comment markers</a>. Lives in
      <code>skills/openpress-apply-comments/</code>.
    </p>
  </ApiEntry>

  <h2>Other skills (handbook content)</h2>

  <p>
    The remaining bundled skills (<code>openpress</code>, <code>openpress-writing</code>,
    <code>openpress-design</code>, <code>openpress-deploy</code>, <code>openpress-diagram-drawing</code>,
    <code>openpress-style-pack-contributor</code>, plus style-pack-specific ones) are <em>handbook
    content</em>: an agent reads them while doing work, but they aren't invoked as discrete
    workflows. The long-term plan is to migrate handbook content into the dogfood document so the
    docs site at <code>/docs/*</code> becomes the single source — but until then, both the skill
    files and these docs pages stay in sync.
  </p>

  <h2>How skills are installed</h2>

  <p>
    Skills install via the <code>skills</code> npm tool, which writes universal skill files into
    <code>.agents/skills/</code> and maintains per-platform mirrors. The OpenPress CLI's
    <code>init</code> runs this automatically:
  </p>

  <Example title="What init does after the template copy" language="bash" code={`npx skills add quan0715/open-press
# → fetches the framework skill bundle
# → writes .agents/skills/{openpress,openpress-writing,...}
# → mirrors into .claude/skills/, .cursor/skills/, etc.`} />

  <p>To refresh later:</p>

  <Example title="Refresh skills" language="bash" code={`npx skills upgrade
# → pulls latest from the same source repo
# → updates the mirrors`} />

  <h2>Authoring custom skills</h2>

  <p>
    A skill is a folder with a <code>SKILL.md</code> describing what the skill does, when an agent
    should invoke it, and the exact steps. Plus optional reference files under
    <code>references/</code>. For style packs, ship a skill under
    <code>skills/&lt;pack-name&gt;/</code> in your pack repo so it installs alongside
    <code>npx skills add github:owner/repo</code>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Detailed skill authoring docs land alongside the slash-command rollout in v0.10.
  </p>

  <h2>Source</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Skills bundle: <a href="https://github.com/quan0715/open-press/tree/main/skills" rel="noopener">github.com/quan0715/open-press/skills</a></li>
    <li>Skills npm tool: <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/skills" rel="noopener">npmjs.com/package/skills</a></li>
  </ul>
</DocLayout>
